## Subscription Lifecycle Rules

### Component Pattern (subscribe-on-load)

```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  if (!resourceId) return;
  // 1. Load data via REST
  const data = await apiRequest(`/resource/${resourceId}`);
  setAtom(data);
  // 2. Subscribe so mutations arrive via WS
  subscribe("resource_type", resourceId);
  return () => {
    // 3. Unsubscribe on unmount
    unsubscribe("resource_type", resourceId);
  };
}, [resourceId]);
```

### Frontend Must Never Poll

No `setInterval`, `setTimeout`-based re-fetch, or periodic `apiRequest` for
any data that has a WS projection. REST is used exclusively for:

1. Initial page load (the first fetch before the subscription is live)
2. Auth flows (token refresh, login, register)
3. Mutations (POST, PUT, DELETE) — these trigger the backend to propagate via WS
4. Lazy one-off reads (e.g. opening a settings panel that rarely changes)

The WS message handler then merges the mutation result back into the atom
without any re-fetch. This means DOM updates happen in O(1) — no round-trip.

